Date: 27 July 2000
From: Stephen Berger <mberger@post.tau.ac.il>
Source: GIDEON <http://www.cyinfo.com>

Background data on _Leishmania donovani_ in Spain
-----------------------------------------
The disease is most common in the southern region. Seroprevalence among
dogs in this region is lowest during April, peaking during October.
Approximately 100 cases [in dogs were reported annually prior to 1987. 98
cases were reported in 1987. A single autochthonous case has been reported
from Minorca. 60 deaths were ascribed to leishmaniasis during 1980 to 1994.
5.25% of dogs in the Madrid area are seropositive.
450 AIDS/Leishmania coinfections [human infections were reported
nationwide during 1990 to 1995 (52.4% of the world's total coinfections);
412 during 1996 to 1998.
2.49% of AIDS patients in the Madrid region are coinfected with visceral
leishmaniasis. Transmission through sharing of needles by intravenous drug
addicts has been reported.
The vectors in Spain are _Phlebotomus [Larroussius ariasi_ and _P.
perniciosus_.
--
Steven Berger
<mberger@post.tau.ac.il>
