[2
Another comment on asymptomatic leishmaniasis:
Wed, 26 Jul 2000 10:43:58 -0400 (EDT)
From: Ellicott McConnell <eck@shore.intercom.net>

Asymptomatic infections with visceral leishmaniasis may be the rule rather
than the exception. While working in an endemic area in the Sudan we found
a constant high _L. donovani_ infection rate in sandflies collected in the
vicinity of local villages. Of the expatriots involved in collecting, three
contracted leishmaniasis, but with only slight dermal manifestations (one
person after only one night's exposure). It seems possible that the
villagers are repeatedly, if not chronically, infected, but suffer clinical
visceral leishmaniasis only when stressed by famine or other factors.
--
Ellicott McConnell, Ph.D.
<eck@shore.intercom.net>
[The data on human cases in Spain clearly shows that leishmaniasis is a
problem which need to be considered in all febrile patients with
unexplained fever of a longer duration who has visited Spain. Leishmania is
a zoonotic infection with reservoir in dogs, and knowledge of the
epidemiology in the dog population will give us an indication and warning
of risks to the human population. The fact that leishmaniasis surfaces as a
problem in HIV/AIDS patients also shows that asymptomatic infection is
common in persons with an adequate immune system, which is emphasized by
the second report. - Mod.EP
..................................ep/es
